Problem Description¶

This Kaggle challenge provides 7613 tweets, which should form the basis for a classification task. The problem consits of distinguishing between disaster related and non desaster related tweets with respect to their respective text.

Furthermore the data contains one keyword as well as a location for each tweet. We will not use both of these features as the single keyword only gives a very narrow insight into the data and can be grosly misleading when a prediction is solely based on it. The location is not of great use either, as disasters can happen at any place and time.

This challenge and the detection of disaster tweets is highly relevant, as different usecases, like automatic monitoring of twitter tweets by disaster relief forces or governments, seem to be possible. This would highly reduce the reaction time of rescue operations in case of an emergency.

The challenge abounds from the fact, that no single simple rule, derived from the text corpus, could describe the way to differentitate between the two types of tweets. On the contrary, we will try to use Natural Language Processing (NLP), which is a branch of artificial intelligence that focuses on enabling computers to understand, interpret, and generate human language, to master the task. In detail we want to employ convolutional and recurrent neural networks with multiple nodes and layers to learn the task and predict the target value for a unknown set of test tweets. Performance of the model is evaluated with the F1 metric, that combines both precision and recall.

The company figure-eight created the dataset and originally shared it on their ‘Data For Everyone’ website. We have obtained the data from Kaggle via the following challenge link: https://www.kaggle.com/c/nlp-getting-started/overview.

The taining set at hand consits of 7613 tweets. Furthermore, the csv has five columns, which are id, keyword, location, text and target. Because of the reasons, outlined in the Problem Description section, we will ignore the columns "keyword" and "location" and focus on the text column, containing the tweet, instead. The "id" column has to be kept, as it functions as an identifier for the specific tweet in the final submission file for the competition.

Regarding the datatypes, we can say, that "id" and "target" are of type integer and boolean respectively, whereas "text" is of type string.

The old character limit before November 2017 at Twitter was 140, which is clearly visible in the distribution of the tweet lengths. The distribution implies that most users fully exhausted the maximum possible number of characters for their tweets. Moreover, we can infer from this facts, that only a minor part of the whole dataset consists of tweets created after November 2017 and when the dataset was published in 2019.

The final fact about the data, that we have to mention, is that it is quite balanced, as 43% of the tweets constitute disaster tweets. This means that we do not have to take special care, when using algorithms that are susceptible for unbalanced datasets.

We can see, that the mean word count is 14.87 with a minimum of 1 and a maximum of 31 in our training dataset. The histogram shows, how the word counts are distributed. One could infer, that the distribution is a normal distribution. However, this impression only arises because of the chosen bin size of 5. If we had choosen a smaller bin size like 1, we would see that the distribution is more of a bi-model type. This is also approved by the normaltest for kurtosis and skewness, which is clearly placed in the rejection region, indicating that we are not dealing with a normal distribution.

One could assume, that hyperlinks do not add much meaning to a tweet. This is why we will try to eliminate them from our dataset. First we will have a look at how many tweets contain hyperlinks.

In [26]:
def remove_hyperlink(x):
    if 'http' in x:
        splitted = x.split()
        splitted_new = [x for x in splitted if not x.startswith('http')]
    else:
        return(x)
    return(' '.join(splitted_new))
print(train.iloc[1308,1])  
train['text'] = train['text'].apply(lambda x: remove_hyperlink(x))
print(train.iloc[1308,1])

Our method seems to work. So we will use this cleaned dataset for our following model building procedure.

Model Architecture¶

We will first use a text vectorization layer, that will transform each tweet into a list of integers, where the integers constitue word indices. The indices relate to the frequence of the respective word in the whole dataset. So the list 1,3 would mean, that the tweet consists of the most common word, followed by the 3th most common word. This approach is described at keras.io (see references).

Afterwards we will follow the architecture describe by Brownlee 2016.

It first uses a Word Embedding layer. This transforms the integer representations of the words into multi-dimensional vectors. These vectors will be more close to each other in cases were words have similar meaning.

This will be followed by a long and short term memory layer, like the ones described in this weeks course. In the sense of Natural Language Processing (NLP), long and short term describes the different levels of meaning in a sentence. Short term would be for example the meaning of words close to each other like a "good" followed by a "morning", whereas long term memory will more likely depict the structure of sentences like relative clauses.

The last layer is a dense output layer with a single output neuron and a sigmoid activation function. This is necessary, because we are dealing with a binary classification problem, where we are only asking for zeros and ones as outputs.

In terms of the computation algorithm we will use a simple log loss or binary cross entropy loss funtion, as this is a binary classification problem. Furthermore, we wil use the Adam optimization algorithm, as described at Brownlee 2016.

Text Vectorization¶

In a real-world setting with an ML model operating online, we would have to think about, how to handle unknown tokens or words (see https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/163005/how-to-set-the-dictionary-for-text-analysis-using-neural-networks/163032#163032 or https://arxiv.org/abs/1707.06961 for possible approaches). This is not a problem in our setting, as we are dealing with a finite set of train and test tweets. So no unknown words will arise during the predicition phase of our task, when we adapt our Vectorizer to the whole vocabulary of the merged datasets.

We have choosen to use a vocabulary size of 5000 which seems to be a good starting point, because a initial run without restrictions yielded a size of around 28000. So we will only use 20% of the most common words or tokens. Furthermore our vectorization layer removes all punctuation from the texts and transforms it to lower case. This should help in getting a standardized output. One could argument that tweets posted in capital letters might indicate more dramatic situations. However, this is tendentious, because capital letters are a common feature in the communcation culture shaped by mediums like Instagram, X, TikTok and others. Furthermore, our text corpuses will be split along whitespaces and the "int" option for outputs yields or preferred output, where the indices of the words indicate their frequency (see explanation above).

We can observe, that our first model achieves a quite good performance of 80% accuracy after the second epoch. Afterwards the model quickly starts to overfit, which can be observed by the decreasing validation accurarcy and the still increasing training accuracy. The loss shows, that we are converging quite good, with a strong decrease in loss during the first epochs. After five epochs we already have centered in the local minimum, as the curve starts to show a asymptotic behaviour. The F1-score that builds the basis for the evaluation of this competition peaks at around 60%. This is not fantastic, but a point to start. In the following section, we will start to build a function around our model definition code, so that we can efficiently test and compare different optimization and model parameters.

Optimization and Model Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Function Definition¶

In [55]:
def run_training_and_evaluation(max_tok,max_length,emb_vec_len,num_lstm_neurons,bat_siz):
    
    out_name = '/kaggle/working/'+'max_tok'+str(max_tok)+'max_l'+str(max_length)+'emb_siz'+str(emb_vec_len)+'lstm'+str(num_lstm_neurons)+'bat'+str(bat_siz)+'.csv'
    
    max_tokens = max_tok
    max_len = max_length

    vectorize_layer = tf.keras.layers.TextVectorization(
        max_tokens=max_tokens,
        standardize="lower_and_strip_punctuation",
        # split="whitespace",
        output_mode='int',
        output_sequence_length=max_len)

    whole_dataset = training['text'].tolist()+validation['text'].tolist()+test['text'].tolist()

    vectorize_layer.adapt(whole_dataset)

    embedding_vector_length = emb_vec_len
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(vectorize_layer)
    model.add(Embedding(input_dim=max_tokens, output_dim=embedding_vector_length, input_length=max_len))
    model.add(LSTM(num_lstm_neurons))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy','F1Score'])#F1Score
    

    hist = model.fit(training['text'].tolist(),training['target'].astype('float32').tolist(), epochs=5, batch_size=bat_siz, validation_data=(validation['text'].tolist(),validation['target'].astype('float32').tolist()))
    
    print(max(hist.history['val_accuracy']))
    print(max(hist.history['val_f1_score']))
    
    epochs = list(range(len(hist.history['val_accuracy'])))
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(9,4.5))
    axs[0].plot(epochs,hist.history['val_accuracy'],label='validation')
    axs[0].plot(epochs,hist.history['accuracy'],label='training')
    axs[0].set_xlabel('epoch')
    axs[0].set_ylim(0.50,1)
    axs[0].legend()
    axs[0].set_title('Accuracy')
    axs[1].plot(epochs,hist.history['loss'],label='training')
    axs[1].set_xlabel('epoch')
    axs[1].set_ylim(0.00,0.7)
    axs[1].legend()
    axs[1].set_title('Loss')

    predictions = model.predict(test['text'].tolist())
    preds = []
    for pred in predictions:
        if pred > 0.5:
            preds.append(1)
        else:
            preds.append(0)

    result = np.column_stack((np.array(test['id']),np.array(preds)))
    result
    result = np.insert(result.astype(str), 0, [['id','target']], axis=0)
    result = pd.DataFrame(result)
    result.to_csv(out_name,header=False, index=False)
    
    return()

With the help of the above function we will in the following test different setups of our model.

Our analysis shows, that in case of our dataset a model with just fifty long-short-term-memory layers is enough to accurately predict the output. More layers do not add any additional performance to the model.

Results and Analysis¶

The single optimization steps have been analized with respect to their results in the hyperparameter tuning section.

We were able to show that simpler models might be the better choice for small datasets with a limited amount of variability in the data. This is underlined by the fact, that a model of just 50 lstm layers, was able to perform as well as a model with double the amount of layers. On the other hand the analysis shows that vocabulary size is key to predictive power even for small datasets. We were not able to achieve good results with less than 5000 tokens.

In summary, we achieved the following results: The best combination of parameters is a maximum amount of tokens of 5000, a amount of considered words of 8, a embedding vector size of 16, combined with 50 lstm layers.

Our best model in terms of the testing set on kaggle, achieved a public kaggle score of 0.77 with leaderboard position 950 on the 17th of November 2023.

Conclusion¶

For me it was really interesting to observe the upper and lower limits of model sizes and their effect on predictins. A key takeaway for me is, that model size is not everything especially for small datasets. In my opinion this is an important lessons, as smaller models are simpler and also more energy efficient and should therefore be prefered. In a future work, I would definitely try to optimize the cleaning procedure of the tweets. In my opinion much potential is lying there, as steps like removing hash-tags, or removing common words, could drastically improve the input for our model and therefore its performance.
